data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The configuration you used in .NET 10 (e.g., `AllowSynchronousIO()` on the Cosmos options) no longer compiles or has no effect.

All your synchronous calls — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime because the Cosmos SDK is inherently async-only.

## The Fix

You must migrate to async methods:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods marked `async`
- Use `ToListAsync()`, `FirstAsync()`, `CountAsync()`, `SaveChangesAsync()`
- Callers up the chain must also be made async (`async` propagates upward)

This is an intentional permanent removal — there's no new opt-in. The sync path was always calling `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` under the hood, risking deadlocks.
